[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The core of Apache Hadoop consists of a storage part, known as Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS), and a processing part which is a MapReduce programming model.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Hadoop splits files into large blocks and distributes them across nodes in a cluster.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] It then transfers packaged code into nodes to process the data in parallel.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] This approach takes advantage of data locality, where nodes manipulate the data they have access to.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] This allows the dataset to be processed faster and more efficiently than it would be in a more conventional supercomputer architecture that relies on a parallel file system where computation and data are distributed via high-speed networking.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Apache Hadoop's MapReduce and HDFS components were inspired by Google papers on MapReduce and Google File System.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop framework itself is mostly written in the Java programming language, with some native code in C and command line utilities written as shell scripts.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Perl language can be easily used with Hadoop Streaming to implement the map and reduce parts of the user's program.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] According to its co-founders, Doug Cutting and Mike Cafarella, the idea of Hadoop was conceived in the Google File System paper that was published in October 2003.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The concept was extended in the Google paper *"MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters".* Development started on the Apache Nutch project, but was moved to the new Hadoop subproject in January 2006.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Doug Cutting, who was working at Yahoo! at the time, named it after his son's toy elephant.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The initial code that was factored out of Nutch consisted of about 5,000 lines of code for HDFS and about 6,000 lines of code for MapReduce.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] In March 2006, Owen O'Malley was the first committer to add to the Hadoop project; Hadoop 0.1.0 was released in April 2006.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] It continues to evolve through contributions that are being made to the project.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The first design document for the Hadoop Distributed File System was written by Dhruba Borthakur in 2007.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Hadoop consists of the *Hadoop Common* package, which provides file system and operating system level abstractions, a MapReduce engine (either MapReduce/MR1 or YARN/MR2) and the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS).
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop Common package contains the Java Archive (JAR) files and scripts needed to start Hadoop.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] For effective scheduling of work, every Hadoop-compatible file system should provide location awareness, which is the name of the rack, specifically the network switch where a worker node is.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Hadoop applications can use this information to execute code on the node where the data is, and, failing that, on the same rack/switch to reduce backbone traffic.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] HDFS uses this method when replicating data for data redundancy across multiple racks.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] This approach reduces the impact of a rack power outage or switch failure; if any of these hardware failures occurs, the data will remain available.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] A small Hadoop cluster includes a single master and multiple worker nodes.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The master node consists of a Job Tracker, Task Tracker, NameNode, and DataNode.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] A slave or *worker node* acts as both a DataNode and TaskTracker, though it is possible to have data-only and compute-only worker nodes.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] These are normally used only in nonstandard applications.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Hadoop requires the Java Runtime Environment (JRE) 1.6 or higher.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The standard startup and shutdown scripts require that Secure Shell (SSH) be set up between nodes in the cluster.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] In a larger cluster, HDFS nodes are managed through a dedicated NameNode server to host the file system index, and a secondary NameNode that can generate snapshots of the namenode's memory structures, thereby preventing file-system corruption and loss of data.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Similarly, a standalone JobTracker server can manage job scheduling across nodes.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop MapReduce is used with an alternate file system, the NameNode, secondary NameNode, and DataNode architecture of HDFS are replaced by the file-system-specific equivalents.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The *Hadoop distributed file system* (HDFS) is a distributed, scalable, and portable file system written in Java for the Hadoop framework.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] A Hadoop instance is divided into HDFS and MapReduce.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] HDFS is used for storing the data and MapReduce is used for processing data.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Top three are Master Services/Daemons/Nodes and bottom two are Slave Services.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Master Services can communicate with each other and in the same way Slave services can communicate with each other.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Name Node is a master node and Data node is its corresponding Slave node and can talk with each other.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Hadoop cluster has nominally a single namenode plus a cluster of datanodes, although redundancy options are available for the namenode due to its criticality.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Each datanode serves up blocks of data over the network using a block protocol specific to HDFS.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The file system uses TCP/IP sockets for communication.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Clients use remote procedure calls (RPC) to communicate with each other.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] HDFS stores large files (typically in the range of gigabytes to terabytes) across multiple machines.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] It achieves reliability by replicating the data across multiple hosts, and hence theoretically does not require redundant array of independent disks (RAID) storage on hosts (but to increase input-output (I/O) performance some RAID configurations are still useful).
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] With the default replication value, 3, data is stored on three nodes: two on the same rack, and one on a different rack.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Data nodes can talk to each other to rebalance data, to move copies around, and to keep the replication of data high.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] HDFS is not fully POSIX-compliant, because the requirements for a POSIX file-system differ from the target goals of a Hadoop application.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The trade-off of not having a fully POSIX-compliant file-system is increased performance for data throughput and support for non-POSIX operations such as Append.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] In May 2012, high-availability capabilities were added to HDFS, letting the main metadata server called the NameNode manually fail-over onto a backup.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The project has also started developing automatic fail-overs.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The HDFS file system includes a so-called *secondary namenode*, a misleading term that some might incorrectly interpret as a backup namenode when the primary namenode goes offline.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] In fact, the secondary namenode regularly connects with the primary namenode and builds snapshots of the primary namenode's directory information, which the system then saves to local or remote directories.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] These checkpointed images can be used to restart a failed primary namenode without having to replay the entire journal of file-system actions, then to edit the log to create an up-to-date directory structure.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Because the namenode is the single point for storage and management of metadata, it can become a bottleneck for supporting a huge number of files, especially a large number of small files.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] HDFS Federation, a new addition, aims to tackle this problem to a certain extent by allowing multiple namespaces served by separate namenodes.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Moreover, there are some issues in HDFS such as small file issues, scalability problems, Single Point of Failure (SPoF), and bottlenecks in huge metadata requests.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] One advantage of using HDFS is data awareness between the job tracker and task tracker.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The job tracker schedules map or reduce jobs to task trackers with an awareness of the data location.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] For example: if node A contains data (a, b, c) and node X contains data (x, y, z), the job tracker schedules node A to perform map or reduce tasks on (a, b, c) and node X would be scheduled to perform map or reduce tasks on (x, y, z).
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] This reduces the amount of traffic that goes over the network and prevents unnecessary data transfer.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop is used with other file systems, this advantage is not always available.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] This can have a significant impact on job-completion times as demonstrated with data-intensive jobs.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] HDFS was designed for mostly immutable files and may not be suitable for systems requiring concurrent write operations.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] HDFS can be mounted directly with a Filesystem in Userspace (FUSE) virtual file system on Linux and some other Unix systems.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] File access can be achieved through the native Java API, the Thrift API (generates a client in a number of languages e.g.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] C++, Java, Python, PHP, Ruby, Erlang, Perl, Haskell, C#, Cocoa, Smalltalk, and OCaml), the command-line interface, the HDFS-UI web application over HTTP, or via 3rd-party network client libraries.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] HDFS is designed for portability across various hardware platforms and for compatibility with a variety of underlying operating systems.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The HDFS design introduces portability limitations that result in some performance bottlenecks, since the Java implementation cannot use features that are exclusive to the platform on which HDFS is running.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Due to its widespread integration into enterprise-level infrastructure, monitoring HDFS performance at scale has become an increasingly important issue.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Monitoring end-to-end performance requires tracking metrics from datanodes, namenodes, and the underlying operating system.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] There are currently several monitoring platforms to track HDFS performance, including Hortonworks, Cloudera, and Datadog.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Hadoop works directly with any distributed file system that can be mounted by the underlying operating system by simply using a `file://` URL; however, this comes at a price – the loss of locality.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] To reduce network traffic, Hadoop needs to know which servers are closest to the data, information that Hadoop-specific file system bridges can provide.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] A number of third-party file system bridges have also been written, none of which are currently in Hadoop distributions.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] However, some commercial distributions of Hadoop ship with an alternative file system as the default – specifically IBM and MapR.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Atop the file systems comes the MapReduce Engine, which consists of one *JobTracker*, to which client applications submit MapReduce jobs.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The JobTracker pushes work to available *TaskTracker* nodes in the cluster, striving to keep the work as close to the data as possible.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] With a rack-aware file system, the JobTracker knows which node contains the data, and which other machines are nearby.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] If the work cannot be hosted on the actual node where the data resides, priority is given to nodes in the same rack.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] This reduces network traffic on the main backbone network.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] If a TaskTracker fails or times out, that part of the job is rescheduled.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The TaskTracker on each node spawns a separate Java virtual machine (JVM) process to prevent the TaskTracker itself from failing if the running job crashes its JVM.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] A heartbeat is sent from the TaskTracker to the JobTracker every few minutes to check its status.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The Job Tracker and TaskTracker status and information is exposed by Jetty and can be viewed from a web browser.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] If one TaskTracker is very slow, it can delay the entire MapReduce job – especially towards the end, when everything can end up waiting for the slowest task.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] With speculative execution enabled, however, a single task can be executed on multiple slave nodes.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] By default Hadoop uses FIFO scheduling, and optionally 5 scheduling priorities to schedule jobs from a work queue.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] In version 0.19 the job scheduler was refactored out of the JobTracker, while adding the ability to use an alternate scheduler (such as the *Fair scheduler* or the *Capacity scheduler*, described next).
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler was developed by Facebook.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The goal of the fair scheduler is to provide fast response times for small jobs and quality of service (QoS) for production jobs.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler has three basic concepts.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Each pool is assigned a guaranteed minimum share.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] By default, jobs that are uncategorized go into a default pool.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Pools have to specify the minimum number of map slots, reduce slots, as well as a limit on the number of running jobs.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler was developed by Yahoo.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler supports several features that are similar to those of the fair scheduler.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Free resources are allocated to queues beyond their total capacity.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Within a queue, a job with a high level of priority has access to the queue's resources.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] There is no preemption once a job is running.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The biggest difference between Hadoop 1 and Hadoop 2 is the addition of YARN (Yet Another Resource Negotiator), which replaced the MapReduce engine in the first version of Hadoop.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] YARN strives to allocate resources to various applications effectively.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] It runs two daemons, which take care of two different tasks: the *resource manager*, which does job tracking and resource allocation to applications, the *application master*, which monitors progress of the execution.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] There are important features provided by Hadoop 3.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] For example, while there is one single *namenode* in Hadoop 2, Hadoop 3, enables having multiple name nodes, which solves the single point of failure problem.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] In Hadoop 3, there are containers working in principle of Docker, which reduces time spent on application development.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] One of the biggest changes is that Hadoop 3 decreases storage overhead with erasure coding.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Also, Hadoop 3 permits usage of GPU hardware within the cluster, which is a very substantial benefit to execute deep learning algorithms on a Hadoop cluster.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The HDFS is not restricted to MapReduce jobs.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] It can be used for other applications, many of which are under development at Apache.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] The list includes the HBase database, the Apache Mahout machine learning system, and the Apache Hive data warehouse.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Theoretically, Hadoop could be used for any workload that is batch-oriented rather than real-time, is very data-intensive, and benefits from parallel processing.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] It can also be used to complement a real-time system, such as lambda architecture, Apache Storm, Flink, and Spark Streaming.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Inc. launched what they claimed was the world's largest Hadoop production application.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Search Webmap is a Hadoop application that runs on a Linux cluster with more than 10,000 cores and produced data that was used in every Yahoo! web search query.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] There are multiple Hadoop clusters at Yahoo! and no HDFS file systems or MapReduce jobs are split across multiple data centers.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Every Hadoop cluster node bootstraps the Linux image, including the Hadoop distribution.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Work that the clusters perform is known to include the index calculations for the Yahoo! search engine.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] In June 2009, Yahoo! made the source code of its Hadoop version available to the open-source community.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] In 2010, Facebook claimed that they had the largest Hadoop cluster in the world with 21 PB of storage.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] In June 2012, they announced the data had grown to 100 PB and later that year they announced that the data was growing by roughly half a PB per day.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] As of 2013, Hadoop adoption had become widespread: more than half of the Fortune 50 companies used Hadoop.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] Influential papers on the birth, growth, and curation of Hadoop and big data processing include: Jeffrey Dean, Sanjay Ghemawat (2004) MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters, Google.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] This paper inspired Doug Cutting to develop an open-source implementation of the Map-Reduce framework.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hadoop] He named it Hadoop, after his son's toy elephant.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Hive provides the necessary SQL abstraction to integrate SQL-like queries (HiveQL) into the underlying Java without the need to implement queries in the low-level Java API.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Hive facilitates the integration of SQL-based querying languages with Hadoop, which is commonly used in data warehousing applications.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] While initially developed by Facebook, Apache Hive is used and developed by other companies such as Netflix and the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority (FINRA).
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Amazon maintains a software fork of Apache Hive included in Amazon Elastic MapReduce on Amazon Web Services.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Apache Hive supports the analysis of large datasets stored in Hadoop's HDFS and compatible file systems such as Amazon S3 filesystem and Alluxio.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] It provides a SQL-like query language called HiveQL with schema on read and transparently converts queries to MapReduce, Apache Tez and Spark jobs.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] All three execution engines can run in Hadoop's resource negotiator, YARN (Yet Another Resource Negotiator).
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] By default, Hive stores metadata in an embedded Apache Derby database, and other client/server databases like MySQL can optionally be used.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The first four file formats supported in Hive were plain text, sequence file, optimized row columnar (ORC) format and RCFile.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Apache Parquet can be read via plugin in versions later than 0.10 and natively starting at 0.13.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Major components of the Hive architecture include the metastore, driver, compiler, optimizer, executor, and user interfaces.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The **metastore** stores metadata for each of the tables, such as their schema and location.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] It also includes partition metadata which helps the driver to track the progress of various data sets distributed over the cluster.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The data is stored in a traditional RDBMS format.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] This metadata enables the driver to keep track of the data.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] A backup server regularly replicates the data to provide recovery in case of data loss.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The **driver** acts like a controller which receives the HiveQL statements.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] It starts the execution of the statement by creating sessions and monitors the life cycle and progress of the execution.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] It stores the necessary metadata generated during the execution of a HiveQL statement.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The driver also acts as a collection point of data or query results obtained after the Reduce operation.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The **compiler** performs compilation of the HiveQL query, converting the query to an execution plan.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] This plan contains the tasks and steps needed to be performed by the Hadoop MapReduce to get the output as translated by the query.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The compiler converts the query to an abstract syntax tree (AST).
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] After checking for compatibility and compile time errors, it converts the AST to a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The DAG divides operators to MapReduce stages and tasks based on the input query and data.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The **optimizer** performs various transformations on the execution plan to produce an optimized DAG.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Transformations can be aggregated together, such as converting a pipeline of joins to a single join, for better performance.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] It can also split tasks, such as applying a transformation on data before a reduce operation, to provide better performance and scalability.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The logic of transformation used for optimization can be modified or pipelined using another optimizer.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] An optimizer called YSmart is a part of Apache Hive.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] This correlated optimizer merges correlated MapReduce jobs into a single MapReduce job, significantly reducing the execution time.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The **executor** executes the tasks after compilation and optimization.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] It interacts with the job tracker of Hadoop to schedule tasks to be run.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] It takes care of pipelining the tasks by making sure that a task with a dependency gets executed only if all other prerequisites have been completed.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] A command-line interface (CLI) provides a user interface for an external user to interact with Hive by submitting queries and instructions and monitoring the process status.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The **Thrift Server** allows external clients to interact with Hive over a network, similar to the JDBC or ODBC protocols.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] While based on SQL, HiveQL does not strictly follow the full SQL-92 standard.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] HiveQL offers extensions not in SQL, including *multi-table inserts,* and *creates tables as select*.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] HiveQL lacked support for transactions and materialized views, and offered only limited subquery support.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Support for insert, update, and delete with full ACID functionality was made available with release 0.14.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Internally, a compiler translates HiveQL statements into a directed acyclic graph of MapReduce, Tez, or Spark jobs, which are submitted to Hadoop for execution.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The word count program counts the number of times each word occurs in the input.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Checks if table docs exists and drops it if it does.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Creates a new table called docs with a single column of type STRING called line.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Loads the specified file or directory (In this case “input_file”) into the table.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] OVERWRITE specifies that the target table to which the data is being loaded into is to be re-written; Otherwise, the data would be appended.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The query `CREATE TABLE word_counts AS SELECT word, count(1) AS count` creates a table called word_counts with two columns: word and count.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] This query draws its input from the inner query `(SELECT explode(split(line, '\s')) AS word FROM docs) temp`, which splits the input words into different rows of a temporary table aliased as temp.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The `GROUP BY WORD` clause groups the results based on their keys, so that the count column holds the number of occurrences for each word of the word column.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The `ORDER BY WORDS` clause sorts the words alphabetically.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The storage and querying operations of Hive resemble those of traditional relational databases.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Although Hive utilizes an SQL-like dialect, differences exist in its structure and operation because it is built on top of the Hadoop ecosystem and operates within the design characteristics of Hadoop and MapReduce.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] A schema is applied to a table in traditional databases.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] In such traditional databases, the table typically enforces the schema when the data is loaded into the table.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] This enables the database to make sure that the data entered follows the representation of the table as specified by the table definition.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] This design is called *schema on write*.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] In comparison, Hive does not verify the data against the table schema on write.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Instead, it subsequently does run time checks when the data is read.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The two approaches have their own advantages and drawbacks.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Checking data against a table schema during load time adds operational overhead, meaning traditional databases require more time to load data.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Verification checks are performed during loading to detect corrupt data prior to query execution.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Because data validation occurs during or immediately after the load stage, subsequent query performance is optimized.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] In contrast, Hive loads data without initial schema verification, resulting in faster data loading but slower query execution times.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Hive can be utilized when the schema is unavailable during data ingestion and is instead defined dynamically at run time.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Transactions are key operations in traditional databases.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] As any typical RDBMS, Hive supports all four properties of transactions (ACID): Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, and Durability.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Transactions in Hive were introduced in Hive 0.13 but were only limited to the partition level.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The recent version of Hive 0.14 had these functions fully added to support complete ACID properties.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Hive 0.14 and later provides different row level transactions such as *INSERT, DELETE and UPDATE*.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Enabling *INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE* transactions require setting appropriate values for configuration properties such as `hive.support.concurrency`, `hive.enforce.bucketing`, and `hive.exec.dynamic.partition.mode`.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Hive v0.7.0 added integration with Hadoop security.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Hadoop began using Kerberos authorization support to provide security.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Kerberos allows for mutual authentication between client and server, where the client's request for a ticket is passed along with the request.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] In earlier versions of Hadoop, users could modify usernames via the `hadoop.job.ugi` property, and MapReduce operations ran under a shared default user identity (such as Hadoop or mapred).
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Following Hive v0.7.0's integration with Hadoop security, TaskTracker jobs are executed by the user who initiated them, and the username can no longer be spoofed by setting the `hadoop.job.ugi` property.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] Permissions for newly created files in Hive are dictated by the HDFS.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The Hadoop distributed file system authorization model uses three entities: user, group and others with three permissions: read, write and execute.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The default permissions for newly created files can be set by changing the unmask value for the Hive configuration variable `hive.files.umask.value`..
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-hive] The default permissions for newly created files can be set by changing the unmask value for the Hive configuration variable `hive.files.umask.value`.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Apache Spark has its architectural foundation in the resilient distributed dataset (RDD), a read-only multiset of data items distributed over a cluster of machines, that is maintained in a fault-tolerant way.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] The Dataframe API was released as an abstraction on top of the RDD, followed by the Dataset API.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] In Spark 1.x, the RDD was the primary application programming interface (API), but as of Spark 2.x use of the Dataset API is encouraged even though the RDD API is not deprecated.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] The RDD technology still underlies the Dataset API.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Spark's RDDs function as a working set for distributed programs that offers a (deliberately) restricted form of distributed shared memory.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Inside Apache Spark the workflow is managed as a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Nodes represent RDDs while edges represent the operations on the RDDs.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Spark facilitates the implementation of both iterative algorithms, which visit their data set multiple times in a loop, and interactive/exploratory data analysis, i.e., the repeated database-style querying of data.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] The latency of such applications may be reduced by several orders of magnitude compared to Apache Hadoop MapReduce implementation.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Among the class of iterative algorithms are the training algorithms for machine learning systems, which formed the initial impetus for developing Apache Spark.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Apache Spark requires a cluster manager and a distributed storage system.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] For cluster management, Spark supports standalone native Spark, Hadoop YARN, Apache Mesos or Kubernetes.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] A standalone native Spark cluster can be launched manually or by the launch scripts provided by the install package.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] It is also possible to run the daemons on a single machine for testing.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] For distributed storage Spark can interface with a wide variety of distributed systems, including Alluxio, Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS), MapR File System (MapR-FS), Cassandra, OpenStack Swift, Amazon S3, Kudu, Lustre file system, or a custom solution can be implemented.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Spark also supports a pseudo-distributed local mode, usually used only for development or testing purposes, where distributed storage is not required and the local file system can be used instead; in such a scenario, Spark is run on a single machine with one executor per CPU core.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Spark Core is the foundation of the overall project.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] This interface mirrors a functional/higher-order model of programming: a "driver" program invokes parallel operations such as map, filter or reduce on an RDD by passing a function to Spark, which then schedules the function's execution in parallel on the cluster.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] These operations, and additional ones such as joins, take RDDs as input and produce new RDDs.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] RDDs are immutable and their operations are lazy; fault-tolerance is achieved by keeping track of the "lineage" of each RDD (the sequence of operations that produced it) so that it can be reconstructed in the case of data loss.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] RDDs can contain any type of Python, .NET, Java, or Scala objects.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Besides the RDD-oriented functional style of programming, Spark provides two restricted forms of shared variables: *broadcast variables* reference read-only data that needs to be available on all nodes, while *accumulators* can be used to program reductions in an imperative style.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] A typical example of RDD-centric functional programming is the following Scala program that computes the frequencies of all words occurring in a set of text files and prints the most common ones.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Each map, flatMap (a variant of map) and reduceByKey takes an anonymous function that performs a simple operation on a single data item (or a pair of items), and applies its argument to transform an RDD into a new RDD.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] PySpark is the Python API for Apache Spark, introduced in Spark 0.7, released in February 2013.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] It allows Spark applications to be written in Python and provides an interactive shell for exploratory analysis.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] PySpark code executes under the standard CPython runtime and can call native Python libraries such as NumPy and SciPy; communication between Python user code and Spark's JVM-based core has historically been mediated by the Py4J library.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] PySpark provides Python interfaces to most of Spark's components, including Spark Core, Spark SQL and the DataFrame API, Structured Streaming, and MLlib; since Spark 4.1 it also exposes the Spark Declarative Pipelines API.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] A pandas-compatible API, known as *pandas API on Spark*, was integrated into PySpark in Apache Spark 3.2.0, released in October 2021.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] It provides equivalents to the pandas data-analysis API that execute against the Spark engine, allowing pandas-style code to be run on distributed data.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] The component originated as Koalas, a separate project open-sourced by Databricks in 2019, which was subsequently merged into PySpark.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] PySpark also provides a client for Spark Connect, a client–server architecture that enables remote connectivity to Spark clusters from PySpark applications.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Spark SQL is a component on top of Spark Core that introduced a data abstraction called DataFrames, which provides support for structured and semi-structured data.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Spark SQL provides a domain-specific language (DSL) to manipulate DataFrames in Scala, Java, Python or .NET.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] It also provides SQL language support, with command-line interfaces and ODBC/JDBC server.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Although DataFrames lack the compile-time type-checking afforded by RDDs, as of Spark 2.0, the strongly typed DataSet is fully supported by Spark SQL as well.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Spark Declarative Pipelines (SDP) is a declarative framework for defining and running extract, transform, load (ETL) data pipelines, added in Apache Spark 4.1.0, which was released on December 16, 2025.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Developers declare the datasets a pipeline should produce and the queries that define them, rather than writing imperative code specifying how each dataset is computed and in what order; Spark constructs a dataflow graph and manages dependency ordering, parallelism, checkpointing, and retries.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] The framework extends Spark's lazy, declarative execution model, previously applied to individual queries through Spark SQL, to pipelines spanning multiple datasets.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Pipelines are defined in SQL or Python and are organized around streaming tables and materialized views, with the underlying transformations expressed as "flows"; batch and streaming computations can be combined within a single pipeline.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Spark Structured Streaming uses Spark Core's fast scheduling capability to perform streaming analytics.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] It ingests data in micro-batches and performs RDD transformations on those micro-batches of data.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] This design enables the same set of application code written for batch analytics to be used in streaming analytics, thus facilitating easy implementation of lambda architecture.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] However, this convenience comes with the penalty of latency equal to the mini-batch duration.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Other streaming data engines that process event by event rather than in micro-batches include Storm and the streaming component of Flink.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Spark Streaming has support built-in to consume from Kafka, Flume, Twitter, ZeroMQ, Kinesis, and TCP/IP sockets.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] In Spark 2.x, a separate technology based on Datasets, called Structured Streaming, that has a higher-level interface is also provided to support streaming.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Apache Spark 4.x added a Real-Time Mode (RTM) execution model for Structured Streaming, with the stated goal of lowering end-to-end latency to support operational and batch workloads on a single engine.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Existing Structured Streaming queries written against the DataFrame and Dataset APIs can be executed under the new mode without modification to the query.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Spark can be deployed in a traditional on-premises data center as well as in the cloud.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Spark Connect is a decoupled client–server architecture for Apache Spark that allows remote applications to connect to a Spark cluster from any environment, introduced in Apache Spark 3.4, released in April 2023.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] The architecture separates the client application from the Spark driver, which historically ran in the same process; under Spark Connect, the client is a thin library that can be embedded in application servers, IDEs, notebooks and other programming environments.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Results are streamed back to the client as Apache Arrow-encoded row batches.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] PySpark support for Spark Connect was added in Spark 3.4, and Scala client support followed in Spark 3.5; additional clients for languages including Go, Swift and Rust have been developed in later releases.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] GraphX is a distributed graph-processing framework on top of Apache Spark.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Because it is based on RDDs, which are immutable, graphs are immutable and thus GraphX is unsuitable for graphs that need to be updated, let alone in a transactional manner like a graph database.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] GraphX provides two separate APIs for implementation of massively parallel algorithms (such as PageRank): a Pregel abstraction, and a more general MapReduce-style API.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Unlike its predecessor Bagel, which was formally deprecated in Spark 1.6, GraphX has full support for property graphs (graphs where properties can be attached to edges and vertices).
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Like Apache Spark, GraphX initially started as a research project at UC Berkeley's AMPLab and Databricks, and was later donated to the Apache Software Foundation and the Spark project.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Apache Spark has built-in support for Scala, Java, SQL, R, Python, and Swift with 3rd party support for the .NET CLR, Julia, and more.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Spark was initially started by Matei Zaharia at UC Berkeley's AMPLab in 2009, and open sourced in 2010 under a BSD license.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] In 2013, the project was donated to the Apache Software Foundation and switched its license to Apache 2.0.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] In February 2014, Spark became a Top-Level Apache Project.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Zaharia's company Databricks set a new world record in large scale sorting using Spark.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Spark had in excess of 1000 contributors in 2015, making it one of the most active projects in the Apache Software Foundation and one of the most active open source big data projects.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Spark 3.5.2 is based on Scala 2.13 (and thus works with Scala 2.12 and 2.13 out-of-the-box), but it can also be made to work with Scala 3.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Apache Spark is developed by a community.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] The project is managed by a group called the "Project Management Committee" (PMC).
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] Feature release branches will, generally, be maintained with bug fix releases for a period of 18 months.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] For example, branch 2.3.x is no longer considered maintained as of September 2019, 18 months after the release of 2.3.0 in February 2018.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] No more 2.3.x releases should be expected after that point, even for bug fixes.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] The last minor release within a major a release will typically be maintained for longer as an “LTS” release.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] For example, 2.4.0 was released on November 2, 2018, and had been maintained for 31 months until 2.4.8 was released in May 2021.
[src:gcp-dataproc/apache-spark] 2.4.8 is the last release and no more 2.4.x releases should be expected even for bug fixes.
[src:gcp-dataproc/cluster-manager] Within cluster and parallel computing, a **cluster manager** is usually backend graphical user interface (GUI) or command-line interface (CLI) software that runs on a set of cluster nodes that it manages (in some cases it runs on a different server or cluster of management servers).
[src:gcp-dataproc/cluster-manager] The cluster manager works together with a cluster management agent.
[src:gcp-dataproc/cluster-manager] These agents run on each node of the cluster to manage and configure services, a set of services, or to manage and configure the complete cluster server itself (see supercomputing.) In some cases the cluster manager is mostly used to dispatch work for the cluster (or cloud) to perform.
[src:gcp-dataproc/cluster-manager] In this last case a subset of the cluster manager can be a remote desktop application that is used not for configuration but just to send work and get back work results from a cluster.
[src:gcp-dataproc/cluster-manager] In other cases the cluster is more related to availability and load balancing than to computational or specific service clusters.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] The United States Census Bureau history illustrates the evolution of data processing from manual through electronic procedures.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] Although widespread use of the term *data processing* dates only from the 1950s, data processing functions have been performed manually for millennia.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] For example, bookkeeping involves functions such as posting transactions and producing reports like the balance sheet and the cash flow statement.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] Completely manual methods were augmented by the application of mechanical or electronic calculators.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] The 1890 United States census schedule was the first to gather data by individual rather than household.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] A number of questions could be answered by making a check in the appropriate box on the form.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] From 1850 to 1880 the Census Bureau employed "a system of tallying, which, by reason of the increasing number of combinations of classifications required, became increasingly complex.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] Only a limited number of combinations could be recorded in one tally, so it was necessary to handle the schedules 5 or 6 times, for as many independent tallies." "It took over 7 years to publish the results of the 1880 census" using manual processing methods.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] The term *automatic data processing* was applied to operations performed by means of unit record equipment, such as Herman Hollerith's application of punched card equipment for the 1890 United States census.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] "Using Hollerith's punchcard equipment, the Census Office was able to complete tabulating most of the 1890 census data in 2 to 3 years, compared with 7 to 8 years for the 1880 census.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] It is estimated that using Hollerith's system saved some $5 million in processing costs" in 1890 dollars even though there were twice as many questions as in 1880.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] Computerized data processing, or electronic data processing represents a later development, with a computer used instead of several independent pieces of equipment.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] The Census Bureau first made limited use of electronic computers for the 1950 United States census, using a UNIVAC I system, delivered in 1952.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] The term *data processing* has mostly been subsumed by the more general term *information technology* (IT).
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] The older term "data processing" is suggestive of older technologies.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] For example, in 1996 the *Data Processing Management Association* (DPMA) changed its name to the *Association of Information Technology Professionals*.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] Nevertheless, the terms are approximately synonymous.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] Commercial data processing involves a large volume of input data, relatively few computational operations, and a large volume of output.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] For example, an insurance company needs to keep records on tens or hundreds of thousands of policies, print and mail bills, and receive and post payments.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] In science and engineering, the terms *data processing* and *information systems* are considered too broad, and the term *data processing* is typically used for the initial stage followed by a data analysis in the second stage of the overall data handling.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] Data analysis uses specialized algorithms and statistical calculations that are less often observed in a typical general business environment.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] For data analysis, software suites like SPSS or SAS, or their free counterparts such as DAP, gretl, or PSPP are often used.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] These tools are usually helpful for processing various huge data sets, as they are able to handle enormous amount of statistical analysis.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] A **data processing system** is a combination of machines, people, and processes that for a set of inputs produces a defined set of outputs.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] The inputs and outputs are interpreted as data, facts, information etc. depending on the interpreter's relation to the system.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] A term commonly used synonymously with *data or storage (codes) processing system* is *information system*.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] With regard particularly to electronic data processing, the corresponding concept is referred to as **electronic data processing system**.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] A very simple example of a data processing system is the process of maintaining a check register.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] Transactions— checks and deposits— are recorded as they occur and the transactions are summarized to determine a current balance.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] Monthly the data recorded in the register is reconciled with a hopefully identical list of transactions processed by the bank.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] A more sophisticated record keeping system might further identify the transactions— for example deposits by source or checks by type, such as charitable contributions.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] This information might be used to obtain information like the total of all contributions for the year.
[src:gcp-dataproc/data-processing] The important thing about this example is that it is a *system*, in which, all transactions are recorded consistently, and the same method of bank reconciliation is used each time.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] In computer science, **parallelism** and concurrency are two different things: a parallel program uses multiple CPU cores, each core performing a task independently.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] On the other hand, concurrency enables a program to deal with multiple tasks even on a single CPU core; the core switches between tasks (i.e. threads) without necessarily completing each one.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] A program can have both, neither or a combination of parallelism and concurrency characteristics.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism, with multi-core and multi-processor computers having multiple processing elements within a single machine, while clusters, MPPs, and grids use multiple computers to work on the same task.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Specialized parallel computer architectures are sometimes used alongside traditional processors, for accelerating specific tasks.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Communication and synchronization between the different subtasks are typically some of the greatest obstacles to getting optimal parallel program performance.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] A theoretical upper bound on the speed-up of a single program as a result of parallelization is given by Amdahl's law, which states that it is limited by the fraction of time for which the parallelization can be utilised.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Traditionally, computer software has been written for serial computation.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] To solve a problem, an algorithm is constructed and implemented as a serial stream of instructions.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] These instructions are executed on a central processing unit on one computer.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Only one instruction may execute at a time—after that instruction is finished, the next one is executed.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Parallel computing, on the other hand, uses multiple processing elements simultaneously to solve a problem.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] This is accomplished by breaking the problem into independent parts so that each processing element can execute its part of the algorithm simultaneously with the others.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The processing elements can be diverse and include resources such as a single computer with multiple processors, several networked computers, specialized hardware, or any combination of the above.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Historically parallel computing was used for scientific computing and the simulation of scientific problems, particularly in the natural and engineering sciences, such as meteorology.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] This led to the design of parallel hardware and software, and high performance computing.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Frequency scaling was the dominant reason for improvements in computer performance from the mid-1980s until 2004.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The runtime of a program is equal to the number of instructions multiplied by the average time per instruction.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Maintaining everything else constant, increasing the clock frequency decreases the average time it takes to execute an instruction.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] An increase in frequency thus decreases runtime for all compute-bound programs.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] However, power consumption *P* by a chip is given by the equation *P* = *C* × *V* 2 × *F*, where *C* is the capacitance being switched per clock cycle (proportional to the number of transistors whose inputs change), *V* is voltage, and *F* is the processor frequency (cycles per second).
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Increases in frequency increase the amount of power used in a processor.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Increasing processor power consumption led ultimately to Intel's May 8, 2004 cancellation of its Tejas and Jayhawk processors, which is generally cited as the end of frequency scaling as the dominant computer architecture paradigm.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] To deal with the problem of power consumption and overheating the major central processing unit (CPU or processor) manufacturers started to produce power efficient processors with multiple cores.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The core is the computing unit of the processor and in multi-core processors each core is independent and can access the same memory concurrently.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Multi-core processors have brought parallel computing to desktop computers.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Thus parallelization of serial programs has become a mainstream programming task.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] In 2012 quad-core processors became standard for desktop computers, while servers had 10+ core processors.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Moore's law predicted that the number of cores per processor would double every 18–24 months.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] By 2023 some processors had over one hundred cores.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Some designs having a mix of performance and efficiency cores (such as ARM's big.LITTLE design) due to thermal and design constraints.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] An operating system can ensure that different tasks and user programs are run in parallel on the available cores.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] However, for a serial software program to take full advantage of the multi-core architecture the programmer needs to restructure and parallelize the code.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] A speed-up of application software runtime will no longer be achieved through frequency scaling, instead programmers will need to parallelize their software code to take advantage of the increasing computing power of multicore architectures.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Optimally, the speedup from parallelization would be linear—doubling the number of processing elements should halve the runtime, and doubling it a second time should again halve the runtime.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] However, very few parallel algorithms achieve optimal speedup.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Most of them have a near-linear speedup for small numbers of processing elements, which flattens out into a constant value for large numbers of processing elements.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The maximum potential speedup of an overall system can be calculated by Amdahl's law.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law indicates that optimal performance improvement is achieved by balancing enhancements to both parallelizable and non-parallelizable components of a task.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Furthermore, it reveals that increasing the number of processors yields diminishing returns, with negligible speedup gains beyond a certain point.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law has limitations, including assumptions of fixed workload, neglecting inter-process communication and synchronization overheads, primarily focusing on computational aspect and ignoring extrinsic factors such as data persistence, I/O operations, and memory access overheads.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Gustafson's law and Universal Scalability Law give a more realistic assessment of the parallel performance.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Understanding data dependencies is fundamental in implementing parallel algorithms.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] No program can run more quickly than the longest chain of dependent calculations (known as the critical path), since calculations that depend upon prior calculations in the chain must be executed in order.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] However, most algorithms do not consist of just a long chain of dependent calculations; there are usually opportunities to execute independent calculations in parallel.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Let *P**i* and *P**j* be two program segments.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions describe when the two are independent and can be executed in parallel.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] For *P**i*, let *I**i* be all of the input variables and *O**i* the output variables, and likewise for *P**j*.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Violation of the first condition introduces a flow dependency, corresponding to the first segment producing a result used by the second segment.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The second condition represents an anti-dependency, when the second segment produces a variable needed by the first segment.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The third and final condition represents an output dependency: when two segments write to the same location, the result comes from the logically last executed segment.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] In this example, instruction 3 cannot be executed before (or even in parallel with) instruction 2, because instruction 3 uses a result from instruction 2.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] It violates condition 1, and thus introduces a flow dependency.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] In this example, there are no dependencies between the instructions, so they can all be run in parallel.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions do not allow memory to be shared between different processes.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] For that, some means of enforcing an ordering between accesses is necessary, such as semaphores, barriers or some other synchronization method.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Subtasks in a parallel program are often called threads.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Some parallel computer architectures use smaller, lightweight versions of threads known as fibers, while others use bigger versions known as processes.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] However, "threads" is generally accepted as a generic term for subtasks.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Threads will often need synchronized access to an object or other resource, for example when they must update a variable that is shared between them.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Without synchronization, the instructions between the two threads may be interleaved in any order.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] If instruction 1B is executed between 1A and 3A, or if instruction 1A is executed between 1B and 3B, the program will produce incorrect data.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The programmer must use a lock to provide mutual exclusion.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] A lock is a programming language construct that allows one thread to take control of a variable and prevent other threads from reading or writing it, until that variable is unlocked.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The thread holding the lock is free to execute its critical section (the section of a program that requires exclusive access to some variable), and to unlock the data when it is finished.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] One thread will successfully lock variable V, while the other thread will be locked out—unable to proceed until V is unlocked again.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] This guarantees correct execution of the program.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Locks may be necessary to ensure correct program execution when threads must serialize access to resources, but their use can greatly slow a program and may affect its reliability.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Locking multiple variables using non-atomic locks introduces the possibility of program deadlock.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] An atomic lock locks multiple variables all at once.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] If it cannot lock all of them, it does not lock any of them.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] If two threads each need to lock the same two variables using non-atomic locks, it is possible that one thread will lock one of them and the second thread will lock the second variable.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] In such a case, neither thread can complete, and deadlock results.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Many parallel programs require that their subtasks act in synchrony.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Barriers are typically implemented using a lock or a semaphore.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] One class of algorithms, known as lock-free and wait-free algorithms, altogether avoids the use of locks and barriers.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] However, this approach is generally difficult to implement and requires correctly designed data structures.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Not all parallelization results in speed-up.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Generally, as a task is split up into more and more threads, those threads spend an ever-increasing portion of their time communicating with each other or waiting on each other for access to resources.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Once the overhead from resource contention or communication dominates the time spent on other computation, further parallelization (that is, splitting the workload over even more threads) increases rather than decreases the amount of time required to finish.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] This problem, known as parallel slowdown, can be improved in some cases by software analysis and redesign.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Applications are often classified according to how often their subtasks need to synchronize or communicate with each other.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] An application exhibits fine-grained parallelism if its subtasks must communicate many times per second; it exhibits coarse-grained parallelism if they do not communicate many times per second, and it exhibits embarrassing parallelism if they rarely or never have to communicate.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Embarrassingly parallel applications are considered the easiest to parallelize.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Flynn created one of the earliest classification systems for parallel (and sequential) computers and programs, now known as Flynn's taxonomy.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Flynn classified programs and computers by whether they were operating using a single set or multiple sets of instructions, and whether or not those instructions were using a single set or multiple sets of data.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-single-data (SISD) classification is equivalent to an entirely sequential program.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-multiple-data (SIMD) classification is analogous to doing the same operation repeatedly over a large data set.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] This is commonly done in signal processing applications.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-single-data (MISD) is a rarely used classification.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] While computer architectures to deal with this were devised (such as systolic arrays), few applications that fit this class materialized.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-multiple-data (MIMD) programs are by far the most common type of parallel programs.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Hennessy, "Some machines are hybrids of these categories, of course, but this classic model has survived because it is simple, easy to understand, and gives a good first approximation.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can incur significant overhead in practice, primarily due to the costs associated with merging data from multiple processes.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Specifically, inter-process communication and synchronization can lead to overheads that are substantially higher—often by two or more orders of magnitude—compared to processing the same data on a single thread.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Therefore, the overall improvement should be carefully evaluated.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] From the advent of very-large-scale integration (VLSI) computer-chip fabrication technology in the 1970s until about 1986, speed-up in computer architecture was driven by doubling computer word size—the amount of information the processor can manipulate per cycle.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Increasing the word size reduces the number of instructions the processor must execute to perform an operation on variables whose sizes are greater than the length of the word.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Historically, 4-bit microprocessors were replaced with 8-bit, then 16-bit, then 32-bit microprocessors.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] This trend generally came to an end with the introduction of 32-bit processors, which has been a standard in general-purpose computing for two decades.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Not until the early 2000s, with the advent of x86-64 architectures, did 64-bit processors become commonplace.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] A computer program is, in essence, a stream of instructions executed by a processor.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Without instruction-level parallelism, a processor can only issue less than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC < 1).
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *subscalar* processors.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] These instructions can be re-ordered and combined into groups which are then executed in parallel without changing the result of the program.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] This is known as instruction-level parallelism.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Advances in instruction-level parallelism dominated computer architecture from the mid-1980s until the mid-1990s.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] All modern processors have multi-stage instruction pipelines.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Each stage in the pipeline corresponds to a different action the processor performs on that instruction in that stage; a processor with an *N*-stage pipeline can have up to *N* different instructions at different stages of completion and thus can issue one instruction per clock cycle (IPC = 1).
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *scalar* processors.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The canonical example of a pipelined processor is a RISC processor, with five stages: instruction fetch (IF), instruction decode (ID), execute (EX), memory access (MEM), and register write back (WB).
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The Pentium 4 processor had a 35-stage pipeline.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Most modern processors also have multiple execution units.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] They usually combine this feature with pipelining and thus can issue more than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC > 1).
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *superscalar* processors.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Superscalar processors differ from multi-core processors in that the several execution units are not entire processors (i.e. processing units).
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Instructions can be grouped together only if there is no data dependency between them.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Scoreboarding and the Tomasulo algorithm (which is similar to scoreboarding but makes use of register renaming) are two of the most common techniques for implementing out-of-order execution and instruction-level parallelism.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Task parallelisms is the characteristic of a parallel program that "entirely different calculations can be performed on either the same or different sets of data".
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] This contrasts with data parallelism, where the same calculation is performed on the same or different sets of data.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Task parallelism involves the decomposition of a task into sub-tasks and then allocating each sub-task to a processor for execution.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The processors would then execute these sub-tasks concurrently and often cooperatively.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Task parallelism does not usually scale with the size of a problem.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Superword level parallelism is a vectorization technique based on loop unrolling and basic block vectorization.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] It is distinct from loop vectorization algorithms in that it can exploit parallelism of inline code, such as manipulating coordinates, color channels or in loops unrolled by hand.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Main memory in a parallel computer is either shared memory (shared between all processing elements in a single address space), or distributed memory (in which each processing element has its own local address space).
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Distributed memory refers to the fact that the memory is logically distributed, but often implies that it is physically distributed as well.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Distributed shared memory and memory virtualization combine the two approaches, where the processing element has its own local memory and access to the memory on non-local processors.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Accesses to local memory are typically faster than accesses to non-local memory.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] On the supercomputers, distributed shared memory space can be implemented using the programming model such as PGAS.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] This model allows processes on one compute node to transparently access the remote memory of another compute node.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] All compute nodes are also connected to an external shared memory system via high-speed interconnect, such as Infiniband, this external shared memory system is known as burst buffer, which is typically built from arrays of non-volatile memory physically distributed across multiple I/O nodes.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Computer architectures in which each element of main memory can be accessed with equal latency and bandwidth are known as uniform memory access (UMA) systems.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Typically, that can be achieved only by a shared memory system, in which the memory is not physically distributed.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] A system that does not have this property is known as a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Distributed memory systems have non-uniform memory access.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Computer systems (with the exception of Groq's LPUs) make use of caches—small and fast memories located close to the processor which store temporary copies of memory values (nearby in both the physical and logical sense).
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Parallel computer systems have difficulties with caches that may store the same value in more than one location, with the possibility of incorrect program execution.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] These computers require a cache coherency system, which keeps track of cached values and strategically purges them, thus ensuring correct program execution.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Bus snooping is one of the most common methods for keeping track of which values are being accessed (and thus should be purged).
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Designing large, high-performance cache coherence systems is a very difficult problem in computer architecture.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] As a result, shared memory computer architectures do not scale and distributed memory systems do.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Parallel computers based on interconnected networks need to have some kind of routing to enable the passing of messages between nodes that are not directly connected.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The medium used for communication between the processors is likely to be hierarchical in large multiprocessor machines.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] This classification is broadly analogous to the distance between basic computing nodes.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] These are not mutually exclusive; for example, clusters of symmetric multiprocessors are relatively common.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] A multi-core processor is a processor that includes multiple processing units (called "cores") on the same chip.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] IBM's Cell microprocessor, designed for use in the Sony PlayStation 3, is a prominent multi-core processor.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Each core in a multi-core processor can potentially be superscalar as well—that is, on every clock cycle, each core can issue multiple instructions from one thread.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Simultaneous multithreading (of which Intel's Hyper-Threading is the best known) was an early form of pseudo-multi-coreism.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] A processor capable of concurrent multithreading includes multiple execution units in the same processing unit—that is it has a superscalar architecture—and can issue multiple instructions per clock cycle from *multiple* threads.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Temporal multithreading on the other hand includes a single execution unit in the same processing unit and can issue one instruction at a time from *multiple* threads.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] A symmetric multiprocessor (SMP) is a computer system with multiple identical processors that share memory and connect via a bus.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Bus contention prevents bus architectures from scaling.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] As a result, SMPs generally do not comprise more than 32 processors.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Because of the small size of the processors and the significant reduction in the requirements for bus bandwidth achieved by large caches, such symmetric multiprocessors are extremely cost-effective, provided that a sufficient amount of memory bandwidth exists.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] A distributed computer (also known as a distributed memory multiprocessor) is a distributed memory computer system in which the processing elements are connected by a network.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Distributed computers are highly scalable.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have a lot of overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] A cluster is a group of loosely coupled computers that work together closely, so that in some respects they can be regarded as a single computer.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Clusters are composed of multiple standalone machines connected by a network.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] While machines in a cluster do not have to be symmetric, load balancing is more difficult if they are not.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The most common type of cluster is the Beowulf cluster, which is a cluster implemented on multiple identical commercial off-the-shelf computers connected with a TCP/IP Ethernet local area network.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Beowulf technology was originally developed by Thomas Sterling and Donald Becker.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] 87% of all Top500 supercomputers are clusters.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The remaining are Massively Parallel Processors, explained below.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Because grid computing systems (described below) can easily handle embarrassingly parallel problems, modern clusters are typically designed to handle more difficult problems—problems that require nodes to share intermediate results with each other more often.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] This requires a high bandwidth and, more importantly, a low-latency interconnection network.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Many historic and current supercomputers use customized high-performance network hardware specifically designed for cluster computing, such as the Cray Gemini network.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] As of 2014, most current supercomputers use some off-the-shelf standard network hardware, often Myrinet, InfiniBand, or Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] A massively parallel processor (MPP) is a single computer with many networked processors.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] MPPs have many of the same characteristics as clusters, but MPPs have specialized interconnect networks (whereas clusters use commodity hardware for networking).
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] MPPs also tend to be larger than clusters, typically having "far more" than 100 processors.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] In an MPP, "each CPU contains its own memory and copy of the operating system and application.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] IBM's Blue Gene/L, the fifth fastest supercomputer in the world according to the June 2009 TOP500 ranking, is an MPP.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Grid computing is the most distributed form of parallel computing.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] It makes use of computers communicating over the Internet to work on a given problem.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Because of the low bandwidth and extremely high latency available on the Internet, distributed computing typically deals only with embarrassingly parallel problems.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Most grid computing applications use middleware (software that sits between the operating system and the application to manage network resources and standardize the software interface).
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The most common grid computing middleware is the Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC).
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Often volunteer computing software makes use of "spare cycles", performing computations at times when a computer is idling.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The ubiquity of the Internet and high-bandwidth networks enabled cloud computing, a model where massively parallel resources are provided as a service.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] This paradigm abstracts the underlying hardware, allowing users to access virtualized clusters for scalable workloads without managing physical infrastructure.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Modern distributed ledger protocols apply parallel computing principles to overcome the sequential bottlenecks of traditional blockchains.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] By sharding the state space, newer consensus architectures allow for "massively parallel transaction processing".
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] In this model, utilized by protocols such as Cerberus, independent transactions are treated as parallel tasks that can be executed simultaneously on different nodes, rather than being processed serially in a single global block.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Within parallel computing, there are specialized parallel devices that remain niche areas of interest.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] While not domain-specific, they tend to be applicable to only a few classes of parallel problems.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Reconfigurable computing is the use of a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) as a co-processor to a general-purpose computer.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] An FPGA is, in essence, a computer chip that can rewire itself for a given task.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] FPGAs can be programmed with hardware description languages such as VHDL or Verilog.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Several vendors have created C to HDL languages that attempt to emulate the syntax and semantics of the C programming language, with which most programmers are familiar.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The best known C to HDL languages are Mitrion-C, Impulse C, and Handel-C.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Specific subsets of SystemC based on C++ can also be used for this purpose.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] AMD's decision to open its HyperTransport technology to third-party vendors has become the enabling technology for high-performance reconfigurable computing.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] General-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU) is a fairly recent trend in computer engineering research.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] GPUs are co-processors that have been heavily optimized for computer graphics processing.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Computer graphics processing is a field dominated by data parallel operations—particularly linear algebra matrix operations.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] In the early days, GPGPU programs used the normal graphics APIs for executing programs.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] However, several new programming languages and platforms have been built to do general purpose computation on GPUs with both Nvidia and AMD releasing programming environments with CUDA and Stream SDK respectively.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Other GPU programming languages include BrookGPU, PeakStream, and RapidMind.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Nvidia has also released specific products for computation in their Tesla series.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The technology consortium Khronos Group has released the OpenCL specification, which is a framework for writing programs that execute across platforms consisting of CPUs and GPUs.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] AMD, Apple, Intel, Nvidia and others are supporting OpenCL.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Several application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) approaches have been devised for dealing with parallel applications.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Because an ASIC is (by definition) specific to a given application, it can be fully optimized for that application.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] As a result, for a given application, an ASIC tends to outperform a general-purpose computer.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] However, ASICs are created by UV photolithography.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] This process requires a mask set, which can be extremely expensive.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] A mask set can cost over a million US dollars.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] (The smaller the transistors required for the chip, the more expensive the mask will be.) Meanwhile, performance increases in general-purpose computing over time (as described by Moore's law) tend to wipe out these gains in only one or two chip generations.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] High initial cost, and the tendency to be overtaken by Moore's-law-driven general-purpose computing, has rendered ASICs unfeasible for most parallel computing applications.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] One example is the PFLOPS RIKEN MDGRAPE-3 machine which uses custom ASICs for molecular dynamics simulation.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] A vector processor is a CPU or computer system that can execute the same instruction on large sets of data.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Vector processors have high-level operations that work on linear arrays of numbers or vectors.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] An example vector operation is *A* = *B* × *C*, where *A*, *B*, and *C* are each 64-element vectors of 64-bit floating-point numbers.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] They are closely related to Flynn's SIMD classification.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Cray computers became famous for their vector-processing computers in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] However, vector processors—both as CPUs and as full computer systems—have generally disappeared.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Modern processor instruction sets do include some vector processing instructions, such as with Freescale Semiconductor's AltiVec and Intel's Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE).
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Concurrent programming languages, libraries, APIs, and parallel programming models (such as algorithmic skeletons) have been created for programming parallel computers.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] These can generally be divided into classes based on the assumptions they make about the underlying memory architecture—shared memory, distributed memory, or shared distributed memory.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Shared memory programming languages communicate by manipulating shared memory variables.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Distributed memory uses message passing.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] POSIX Threads and OpenMP are two of the most widely used shared memory APIs, whereas Message Passing Interface (MPI) is the most widely used message-passing system API.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] One concept used in programming parallel programs is the future concept, where one part of a program promises to deliver a required datum to another part of a program at some future time.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Efforts to standardize parallel programming include an open standard called OpenHMPP for hybrid multi-core parallel programming.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The OpenHMPP directive-based programming model offers a syntax to efficiently offload computations on hardware accelerators and to optimize data movement to/from the hardware memory using remote procedure calls.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The rise of consumer GPUs has led to support for compute kernels, either in graphics APIs (referred to as compute shaders), in dedicated APIs (such as OpenCL), or in other language extensions.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Automatic parallelization of a sequential program by a compiler is the "holy grail" of parallel computing, especially with the aforementioned limit of processor frequency.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Despite decades of work by compiler researchers, automatic parallelization has had only limited success.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Mainstream parallel programming languages remain either explicitly parallel or (at best) partially implicit, in which a programmer gives the compiler directives for parallelization.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] A few fully implicit parallel programming languages exist—SISAL, Parallel Haskell, SequenceL, SystemC (for FPGAs), Mitrion-C, VHDL, and Verilog.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] As a computer system grows in complexity, the mean time between failures usually decreases.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing is a technique whereby the computer system takes a "snapshot" of the application—a record of all current resource allocations and variable states, akin to a core dump—; this information can be used to restore the program if the computer should fail.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing means that the program has to restart from only its last checkpoint rather than the beginning.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] While checkpointing provides benefits in a variety of situations, it is especially useful in highly parallel systems with a large number of processors used in high performance computing.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] As parallel computers become larger and faster, we are now able to solve problems that had previously taken too long to run.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Fields as varied as bioinformatics (for protein folding and sequence analysis) and economics have taken advantage of parallel computing.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can also be applied to the design of fault-tolerant computer systems, particularly via lockstep systems performing the same operation in parallel.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] This provides redundancy in case one component fails, and also allows automatic error detection and error correction if the results differ.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] These methods can be used to help prevent single-event upsets caused by transient errors.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Although additional measures may be required in embedded or specialized systems, this method can provide a cost-effective approach to achieve n-modular redundancy in commercial off-the-shelf systems.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The origins of true (MIMD) parallelism go back to Luigi Federico Menabrea and his *Sketch of the Analytic Engine Invented by Charles Babbage*.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] In 1957, Compagnie des Machines Bull announced the first computer architecture specifically designed for parallelism, the Gamma 60.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] It utilized a fork-join model and a "Program Distributor" to dispatch and collect data to and from independent processing units connected to a central memory.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] In April 1958, Stanley Gill (Ferranti) discussed parallel programming and the need for branching and waiting.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Also in 1958, IBM researchers John Cocke and Daniel Slotnick discussed the use of parallelism in numerical calculations for the first time.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Burroughs Corporation introduced the D825 in 1962, a four-processor computer that accessed up to 16 memory modules through a crossbar switch.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] In 1967, Amdahl and Slotnick published a debate about the feasibility of parallel processing at American Federation of Information Processing Societies Conference.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] It was during this debate that Amdahl's law was coined to define the limit of speed-up due to parallelism.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] In 1969, Honeywell introduced its first Multics system, a symmetric multiprocessor system capable of running up to eight processors in parallel.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] C.mmp, a multi-processor project at Carnegie Mellon University in the 1970s, was among the first multiprocessors with more than a few processors.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The first bus-connected multiprocessor with snooping caches was the Synapse N+1 in 1984.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] SIMD parallel computers can be traced back to the 1970s.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The motivation behind early SIMD computers was to amortize the gate delay of the processor's control unit over multiple instructions.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] In 1964, Slotnick had proposed building a massively parallel computer for the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] His design was funded by the US Air Force, which was the earliest SIMD parallel-computing effort, ILLIAC IV.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The key to its design was a fairly high parallelism, with up to 256 processors, which allowed the machine to work on large datasets in what would later be known as vector processing.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] However, ILLIAC IV was called "the most infamous of supercomputers", because the project was only one-fourth completed, but took 11 years and cost almost four times the original estimate.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] When it was finally ready to run its first real application in 1976, it was outperformed by existing commercial supercomputers such as the Cray-1.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] In the early 1970s, at the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert started developing the *Society of Mind* theory, which views the biological brain as massively parallel computer.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] In 1986, Minsky published *The Society of Mind*, which claims that "mind is formed from many little agents, each mindless by itself".
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] The theory attempts to explain how what we call intelligence could be a product of the interaction of non-intelligent parts.
[src:gcp-dataproc/parallel-computing] Minsky says that the biggest source of ideas about the theory came from his work in trying to create a machine that uses a robotic arm, a video camera, and a computer to build with children's blocks.
